<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I>Description of Annual and Long-Term Incentive Awards in the 2017 Summary Compensation Table
and the Grants of Plan-Based Awards in 2017 Table </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Annual Incentive Plan: Cash Bonuses and SLO Awards</I>. Each of the named executive officers has a
target bonus that is established by the Compensation Committee during the first quarter of the year. Also, each of the named executive officers has the opportunity at a time determined by the Compensation Committee (generally prior to the start of
the performance year) to designate a portion of his or her annual bonus to be received as a SLO award under the 2014 Omnibus Incentive Plan. The portion to be denominated as SLO awards, in increments of 25% of the annual bonus, may be given a
premium to be determined by the Compensation Committee each year. The stock price used to calculate the number of shares that can be earned is the closing price on the first trading day of the performance year, thereby reflecting stock price changes
during the performance year in the value of the SLO award. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Once the amount of the annual bonus that has been earned has been determined for each named executive
officer following the end of the year, the cash portion is paid out shortly thereafter, and the SLO award is provided in the form of an award of restricted stock units under the 2014 Omnibus Incentive Plan that vest on the second anniversary of the
grant date. The award is granted on a date determined by the Compensation Committee, but no later than March&nbsp;15 following the end of the performance year. For the &#147;principal portion&#148; of the award that would have otherwise been paid in
cash, the award vests earlier upon any termination of employment, other than for cause. For the &#147;premium portion&#148; of the award equal to the additional 25%, the award vests earlier only in case of death, disability or retirement. Retirement
for the purpose of SLO awards and the PSU awards described below means termination of employment after five or more years of employment and with years of employment plus age equal to 70 or more, except termination for cause. Except as described
above, if the recipient ceases to be employed by us prior to vesting, then the award is forfeited, except for certain circumstances following a change in control. SLO awards in the form of restricted stock units have no voting rights until shares
are issued to them but do receive a cash payment in the amount of the dividends (without interest) on the shares they have earned at about the same time that shares are issued to them following the period of restriction. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Performance Share Unit Awards</I>. PSU awards, which were awarded under the 2014 Omnibus Incentive Plan, generally provide for a three-year performance period with a
targeted number of shares to be earned if performance during the period meets goals set by the Compensation Committee during the first 90 days of the period. If performance is below defined threshold levels, then no units will be earned, and if
performance exceeds defined maximum levels, then a maximum number of units (above the target number) will be earned. PSU awards are not transferable by the participant until the end of the performance period and certification by the Compensation
Committee with respect to each performance measure used for the award. If a participant terminates employment during the performance period due to death, disability or retirement, then the participant (or his or her estate) will receive a pro rata
payout following the end of the performance period based on the portion of the performance period during which the participant was employed and based on the number of units that would have been earned by the participant if he or she had remained
employed for the entire performance period prior to applying the pro rata factor. If the participant leaves employment during the performance period for any other reason, then the units are forfeited, except for certain circumstances following a
change in control. Special retirement provisions apply to Mr.&nbsp;Peribere under his 2012 employment agreement and the additional agreement entered into in January 2016 to extend the term of his employment to December&nbsp;31, 2017. At about the
same time that shares are issued to participants following the performance period, participants also receive a cash payment in the amount of the dividends (without interest) that would have been paid during the performance period on the number of
shares that they have earned. Holders of PSU awards have no voting rights as stockholders until shares of common stock are issued after the end of the performance period. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right">57 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Restricted Stock and Restricted Stock Units</I>. Awards of restricted stock and restricted stock units included in
&#147;&#151;2017 Summary Compensation Table&#148; were made under the 2014 Omnibus Incentive Plan, which awards provide for a vesting period. Awards vest earlier in the event of the participant&#146;s death or disability. If a participant terminates
employment prior to vesting, then the award of restricted stock or restricted stock units is forfeited, except for certain circumstances following a change in control. Within 90 days following the date of termination, the Compensation Committee can
waive the forfeiture of all or a portion of an award. Special retirement provisions apply to Mr.&nbsp;Peribere under his 2012 employment agreement and the additional agreement entered into in January 2016 to extend the term of his employment to
December&nbsp;31, 2017. During the vesting period, holders of unvested shares of restricted stock (but not holders of unvested shares of restricted stock units) are entitled to receive dividends on the same basis as dividends are paid to other
stockholders and are entitled to vote the unvested shares. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I><A NAME="toc554645_31"></A>Outstanding Equity Awards at 2017 Fiscal <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Year-End</FONT> </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows, as of December&nbsp;31, 2017, outstanding and unvested stock awards under the 2014
Omnibus Incentive Plan for the named executive officers. All market or payout values in the table shown for stock awards are based on the closing price of common stock on December&nbsp;29, 2017 of $49.30 per share. No awards were outstanding as of
December&nbsp;31, 2017 for Ms.&nbsp;Lowe as a result of her resignation during 2017. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

&#147;principal portion&#148; or (b)&nbsp;in case of death, disability or retirement with respect to the &#147;premium portion.&#148; As of December&nbsp;31, 2017, Mr.&nbsp;Deily is retirement eligible. </TD></TR></TABLE>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">3</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The market or payout values shown in this column are based on the closing price of common stock on December&nbsp;29, 2017 of $49.30 per share as reported on the NYSE. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">4</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">16PSU awards are performance share unit awards for the performance period January&nbsp;1, 2016 through December&nbsp;31, 2018 that vest on the latter date. The amounts shown in this column for 16PSU awards represent
32.5% of the target number of shares (i.e., threshold) based on performance through December&nbsp;31, 2017. 17PSU awards are performance share unit awards for the performance period January&nbsp;1, 2017 through December&nbsp;31, 2019 that vest on
the latter date. The amounts shown in this column for 17PSU awards represent 100% of the target number of shares based on performance through December&nbsp;31, 2017. The PSUs are not settled until after the end of the performance period when
performance results are certified by the Compensation Committee, usually at the regularly scheduled meeting in February, which generally approximates three years after the original grant date. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I><A NAME="toc554645_32"></A>Stock Vested in 2017 </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the number of shares vesting for stock awards for the named executive officers during 2017, as well as the value of the shares realized upon
vesting. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="40%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="17%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="21%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="15%"></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#12737c" STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ROWSPAN="2" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Name</FONT></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #ffffff">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" COLSPAN="3" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #ffffff"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Stock Award</FONT></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ROWSPAN="2" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT
 COLOR="#ffffff">Value&nbsp;Realized</FONT></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">On&nbsp;Vesting</FONT></B></FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I><A NAME="toc554645_33"></A>Pension Benefits in 2017 </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Deily participates in the Sealed Air Corporation Restoration Plan for Cryovac Employees, a component plan of the Sealed Air Combined Pension Plan and a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined benefit plan that covers the employees of our Cryovac operations who participated in a defined benefit plan maintained by a prior employer immediately prior to March&nbsp;31, 1998. </P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Payment&nbsp;During&nbsp;</FONT></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Last Fiscal Year&nbsp;</FONT></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">($)&nbsp;</FONT></B></FONT></P></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Deily</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">Restoration&nbsp;Plan&nbsp;for&nbsp;Cryovac<BR>Employees</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" ALIGN="right">34.0833</TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">0</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">0</TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Restoration Plan for Cryovac Employees provides a retirement benefit that is based on the amount by which the benefit assuming the
participant had remained in the prior employer&#146;s defined benefit plan until retirement exceeds assumed benefits under our Profit-Sharing Plan plus the accrued benefit as of March&nbsp;31, 1998 under the prior employer&#146;s plan. This
calculation resulted in an accumulated benefit for Mr.&nbsp;Deily of $0 at December&nbsp;31, 2017. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The number of years of credited service at December&nbsp;31,
2017 includes service with the prior employer of 15.3 years for Mr.&nbsp;Deily. The present value of the accumulated benefit at December&nbsp;31, 2017 is calculated assuming a retirement age of 65. The Restoration Plan for Cryovac Employees provides
for normal retirement at age 65 and early retirement at age 55. Benefits are generally paid as a single life annuity, but benefits may be paid in other forms, including joint and survivor annuities. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The normal retirement benefit is a monthly amount equal to the excess of (a)&nbsp;the sum of 1% of the average of the annual compensation for the highest five
consecutive <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">12-month</FONT> periods during the last 15 years of service (the final average compensation) plus 0.4 of 1% of the final average compensation in excess of the average Social Security wage bases during the
35 years ending with the year in which the participant attains Social Security retirement age, multiplied by the years of credited service, over (b)&nbsp;the accrued monthly benefit as of March&nbsp;31, 1998 under the defined benefit plan maintained
by the prior employer plus the participant&#146;s assumed accrued benefit under our Profit-Sharing Plan. The early retirement benefit is calculated in a similar manner after applying actuarial equivalent factors to the calculation described in
(a)&nbsp;of the preceding sentence and based on the early retirement factors in effect on March&nbsp;31, 1998 under the defined benefit plan maintained by the prior employer. The participant&#146;s assumed accrued benefit under our Profit-Sharing
Plan is determined by crediting 10% annual interest prior to 2003 and 8.5% annual interest beginning in 2003 to our contributions to the Profit-Sharing Plan each year from the date of contribution to the date of determination, summing all of these
adjusted contributions, and converting the result to an annual benefit payable for the life of the participant. The Restoration Plan for Cryovac Employees also provides a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-retirement</FONT> death benefit in the
amount of 75% of the normal retirement benefit under a 75% joint and survivor annuity that would commence on the participant&#146;s 65th birthday. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Restoration
Plan for Cryovac Employees was amended to freeze benefit accruals as of December&nbsp;31, 2016, and as a result, no additional benefits will be accrued under the Restoration Plan for Cryovac Employees after 2016. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">60 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Each year the Deferred Compensation Plan for Key Employees permits participating employees to elect to defer (a)&nbsp;up to 50% of base salary for the year and
(b)&nbsp;up to 100% of the cash annual incentive award for the year payable under our Annual Incentive Plan. Our Deferred Compensation Plan for Key Employees permits discretionary contributions by us. Participant account balances are credited with
interest as determined by the Compensation Committee, which has determined that accounts will be adjusted monthly based on the Moody&#146;s Seasoned Aaa Corporate Bond Yield for that month. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">A participant&#146;s account will be distributed based on the participant&#146;s payment election made at the time of deferral. A participant can elect to have
deferrals credited to a &#147;retirement account&#148; to be paid in a lump sum or installments (over 5, 10 or 15 years) commencing the seventh month after termination of employment or at a later age or date selected by the participant.
Alternatively, a participant can have up to two <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;in-service</FONT> accounts&#148; that will be payable in a lump sum or 5 annual installments on a date specified by the participant (or earlier upon a termination
of employment). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I><A NAME="toc554645_35"></A>Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We do not have any severance programs or agreements covering any of our named executive officers, except for the arrangements described below and benefits generally
available to salaried employees, also noted below. We also have no programs or agreements providing any payments or benefits to our named executive officers in connection with a change in control, except as part of our equity compensation awards and
Executive Severance Plan as discussed in more detail below. The following describes arrangements that address cash payments or other benefits to certain of our named executive officers following termination of employment: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><I>Peribere Employment Agreement</I>:&nbsp;When he was hired, Mr.&nbsp;Peribere signed an employment agreement, and portions of that agreement were modified by an agreement entered into in January 2016 in connection
with the extension of the term of his employment. See the discussion above in &#147;&#151;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#151;Employment, Severance and Change in Control Arrangements&#148; for more details. Although the agreement included
provisions regarding severance in case of an involuntary termination without cause during the employment term, as a result of Mr.&nbsp;Peribere&#146;s retirement on December&nbsp;31, 2017, no severance was payable. (Note that the treatment of
Mr.&nbsp;Peribere&#146;s equity awards that were granted under the employment agreement upon a termination of employment or a change in control is discussed below.) </TD></TR></TABLE>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><I>Doheny Offer Letter Agreement. </I>Mr.&nbsp;Doheny&#146;s offer letter agreement includes severance protection if Mr.&nbsp;Doheny&#146;s employment is terminated by us without &#147;cause&#148; or by Mr.&nbsp;Doheny
for &#147;good reason&#148; (as those terms are defined in the offer letter agreement). If the termination of employment occurs other than within 24 months after a change in control, the cash severance equals two times his annual salary and target
annual bonus. If the termination of employment occurs on or within 24 months after a change in control, the cash severance equals three times the sum of his salary and target annual bonus. Payments for a pro rata bonus and premiums for certain
health benefits may also apply. The offer letter agreement does not provide for any tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-ups</FONT> for excise taxes for payments in connection with a change in control, and instead provides for a &#147;best
net&#148; cutback consistent with our standard practice for other senior executives. Payment of severance is conditioned on Mr.&nbsp;Doheny providing us with a release of claims and complying with applicable covenants. Upon a termination without
cause or with good reason on December&nbsp;31, 2017, Mr.&nbsp;Doheny would have received the amount of severance benefits shown in the table below. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:6%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If a termination without cause or for good reason occurs upon or within two years after a change in control, the employee
is instead entitled to receive (a)&nbsp;a lump sum payment equal to two years of base salary, (b)&nbsp;continued health and welfare benefits for up to 18 months, and (c)&nbsp;accelerated vesting of all outstanding equity compensation awards. For
this purpose, and consistent with the current provisions of our stockholder-approved 2014 Omnibus Incentive Plan, accelerated vesting of any performance-based equity awards is based on assumed achievement of performance goals at the greater of
target performance or actual performance measured through the last quarter preceding the change in control. Additional details on treatment of equity awards upon termination of employment or following a change in control can be found below. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:6%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Executive Severance Plan was amended in February 2018 to make two changes: (a)&nbsp;for an involuntary termination not in connection with a change in
control, the severance period will be fixed as 12 months; and (b)&nbsp;for cash severance, the severance will be based on the sum of the covered executive&#146;s salary and target annual bonus. The table below shows the value of severance benefits
under the Executive Severance Plan as in effect on December&nbsp;31, 2017, before this amendment became effective. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:6%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Severance benefits are
conditioned upon an employee giving us a general release of claims at the time of separation. Benefits are also conditioned upon an employee&#146;s compliance with certain restrictive covenants regarding
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-disparagement,</FONT> confidentiality, and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> (in addition to any other restrictive covenants to which an employee may be subject). No tax <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-ups</FONT> are provided to any participant under the Plan in case of any excise taxes under </P>

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">**</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">This column includes lump sum payments equal to two years of salary plus the estimated value of continued benefits for 18 months, except that for Mr.&nbsp;Doheny it includes (a)&nbsp;three times the sum of his annual
salary and target annual bonus and (b)&nbsp;two times the cost of certain benefits. The column excludes the value of any accelerated vesting of equity compensation awards (see following table). </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our incentive award programs include provisions addressing the extent to which the award becomes vested and payable or is forfeited upon termination of employment. The
following briefly describes the key features of these provisions. See also &#147;&#151;Description of Annual and Long-Term Incentive Awards in the 2017 Summary Compensation Table and the Grants of Plan-Based Awards in 2017 Table&#148; for more
details. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><I>Annual Bonus Awards: </I>Under our Annual Incentive Plan, employees must remain employed through the applicable payment date in order to be entitled to receive an annual bonus for a year; otherwise, payment of the
annual bonus is at our discretion. Bonuses are paid during the month of March for the prior year, so termination of the named executive officers as of the end of 2017 would have meant that they were not entitled to receive a cash bonus or SLO award
based on 2017 performance. For a termination of employment before the bonus payment date, the payment of an annual bonus is discretionary depending on the circumstances. Under his offer letter agreement, however, Mr.&nbsp;Doheny will receive a pro
rata annual bonus in case of a termination without cause or for good reason. The annual bonus paid (as cash and/or SLO award) under the Annual Incentive Plan to each named executive officer for 2017 was as follows: Mr.&nbsp;Peribere, $2,055,625,
Mr.&nbsp;Stiehl, $192,523; Mr.&nbsp;Doheny, $502,180; Mr.&nbsp;Chammas, $589,098; and Mr.&nbsp;Deily, $437,996. These amounts may not represent the amounts that would have been awarded if the named executive officers had terminated employment at the
end of 2017 for any of the reasons noted above. As noted earlier, Ms.&nbsp;Lowe did not receive a 2017 Annual Incentive Plan award because of her resignation during 2017. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:10pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt"><I>Restricted Stock and Restricted Stock Units: </I>These awards will vest in full in case of death or disability before
the scheduled vesting date and will generally forfeit for any other termination of employment before the scheduled vesting date with six exceptions. First, SLO awards that have been awarded as RS or RSUs after the end of the performance year will
vest in full upon retirement. Second, RS and RSUs will vest upon a termination of employment by us without cause or by the executive with good reason that occurs within two years after a change in control. Third, for SLO awards, the &#147;principal
portion&#148; that would have otherwise been paid in cash vests in full upon any termination other than a termination for cause. Fourth, Mr.&nbsp;Doheny&#146;s offer letter agreement provides for prorated vesting of his new hire RSUs (subject to
actual </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right">63 </P>

</DIV></Center>

performance results for the performance-vesting RSUs) if he has been terminated without cause or terminates with good reason on or before December&nbsp;31, 2020. Sixth, within 90 days following
the date of termination, the Compensation Committee can waive the forfeiture of RS or RSUs. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:10pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><I>Performance Share Units</I>: Termination of employment before the end of the performance period generally results in the forfeiture of any outstanding PSU awards with two exceptions. First, in case of death,
disability or retirement before the end of the performance period, a pro rata number of the PSUs will become payable after the end of the performance period, based on the actual performance results for the performance period. Second, in case of a
change in control followed within two years by a termination of employment without cause or by the executive with good reason (a &#147;qualifying termination&#148; for purposes of the table below), per the Executive Severance Plan, the PSUs will
become payable as of the date of termination based on target performance (or actual performance through the quarter prior to the change in control, if greater). In addition, under Mr.&nbsp;Peribere&#146;s 2012 employment agreement and January 2016
agreement, for PSUs granted in 2016 and 2017 (including the PSUs granted as an inducement to his entering into the January 2016 agreement), in case of termination by us without cause or upon completion of the term of employment ending
December&nbsp;31, 2017 (subject to certain conditions related to succession planning and compliance with employment-related covenants), the PSUs will vest in full (not prorated) subject to actual performance results. Based on
Mr.&nbsp;Peribere&#146;s retirement on December&nbsp;31, 2017, these provisions were triggered for his outstanding PSUs, which based on the closing price of our common stock of $49.30 as of December&nbsp;29, 2017 were valued at $10,637,461 (assuming
threshold performance for the 2016 PSUs and target performance for the 2017 PSUs). </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the amounts that would have been payable
to the named executive officers under these equity award programs for a termination of employment as of December&nbsp;31, 2017, based on the closing price of our common stock of $49.30 as of December&nbsp;29, 2017. All awards remain subject to the
Recoupment Policy (discussed in &#147;&#151;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; above). Mr.&nbsp;Peribere is excluded because he retired on December&nbsp;31, 2017 and Ms.&nbsp;Lowe is excluded because she resigned effective October&nbsp;31,
2017. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The benefits described or referenced above are in addition to benefits available generally to salaried employees upon
termination of employment, such as, for employees in the United States, distributions under our 401(k) Thrift Plan and our Profit-Sharing Plan, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-subsidized</FONT> retiree medical benefits, disability benefits and
accrued vacation pay (if applicable). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I><A NAME="toc554645_36"></A>CEO Pay Ratio </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As required by applicable SEC rules, we are providing the following estimate of the relationship of the annual total compensation of our employees and the annual total
compensation of Jerome A. Peribere, our President and CEO as of the end of 2017, our last completed fiscal year. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For 2017: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:10pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">the median of the annual total compensation of all our employees, other than our CEO, was $61,031; and </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:10pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">the annual total compensation of our CEO, as reported in &#147;Executive Compensation&#151;2017 Summary Compensation Table&#148; (and adjusted as noted below), was $10,900,704. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Based on this information, we reasonably estimate that for 2017 our CEO&#146;s annual total compensation was approximately 179 times that of the median of the annual
total compensation of all our employees. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We took the following steps to identify the median of the annual total compensation of all our employees, as well as to
determine the annual total compensation of our median employee and our CEO. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:10pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">1.</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">We determined that, as of December&nbsp;31, 2017, our employee population consisted of approximately 14,120 individuals. This population consisted of our full-time, part-time and temporary employees employed with us as
of the determination date. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:10pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">2.</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">To identify the &#147;median employee&#148; from our employee population, we used total annual salary (including base wages for hourly employees) that each employee was paid for 2017 before any taxes, deductions,
insurance, premiums and other payroll withholding, plus any 2017 target bonus amount. We did not use any statistical sampling techniques. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:10pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">3.</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For the annual total compensation of our median employee, we identified and calculated the elements of that employee&#146;s compensation for 2017 in accordance with the requirements of Item 402(c)(2)(x) of Regulation <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">S-K,</FONT> except that we also included the estimated value of certain broad-based group health and life benefits, resulting in annual total compensation of $61,031. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:10pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">4.</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For the annual total compensation of our CEO, we used the amount reported in the &#147;Total&#148; column in &#147;Executive Compensation&#151;2017 Summary Compensation Table.&#148; However, to maintain consistency
between the annual total compensation of our CEO and the median employee, we also added the estimated value of certain broad-based group health and life benefits for our CEO to the amount reported in that table. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The CEO pay ratio reported above is a reasonable estimate calculated in a manner consistent with SEC rules based on the methodologies and assumptions described above.
SEC rules for identifying the median employee and determining the CEO pay ratio permit companies to employ a wide range of methodologies, estimates and assumptions. As a result, the CEO pay ratios reported by other companies, which may have employed
other permitted methodologies or assumptions and which may have a significantly different work force structure from ours, are likely not comparable to our CEO pay ratio. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right">65 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><B><I><A NAME="toc554645_38"></A>Proposal 2. </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><B><I>Amendment and Restatement of 2014 Omnibus Incentive Plan </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><B><I>Introduction </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We use equity compensation
awards to provide long-term incentive compensation and to attract and retain highly regarded employees and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> directors. Our board believes that our equity compensation program is an integral part of
our approach to long-term incentive compensation, focused on shareholder return, and our continuing efforts to align shareholder and management interests. We believe that growth in shareholder value depends on, among other things, our continued
ability to attract and retain employees, in a competitive workplace market, with the experience and capacity to perform at the highest levels. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The 2014 Omnibus
Incentive Plan, or the Omnibus Plan, was approved by our stockholders in 2014. The Omnibus Plan authorized the issuance, pursuant to awards under the plan, of up to 4,250,000 shares of our common stock plus any shares that were available for
issuance under its predecessor plans. As of March&nbsp;19, 2018, there were about 1.4&nbsp;million shares available for future grants under the Omnibus Plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In
view of the limited number of shares remaining available under the Omnibus Plan, our board approved an amendment and restatement of the Omnibus Plan, or the Amended Plan, a copy of which appears as Annex D to this Proxy Statement, subject to
shareholder approval. If our stockholders do not approve the Amended Plan, the Omnibus Plan will remain in effect in its current form. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Amended Plan adds
2.2&nbsp;million shares of common stock to the share pool previously available under the Omnibus Plan. The Amended Plan makes certain other minor changes to the plan, including the addition of minimum vesting requirements as described below. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Omnibus Plan includes design features intended to allow awards that qualify as &#147;performance-based compensation&#148; under Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Internal
Revenue Code. These awards are intended to be exempt from the $1&nbsp;million deduction limit that would otherwise apply under Section&nbsp;162(m) for compensation paid to certain executive officers. The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act eliminated the
&#147;performance-based compensation&#148; exception effective 2018. The Amended Plan retains certain individual award limits and a list of permitted performance criteria, even though those features are no longer required by the Tax Cuts and Jobs
Act for future awards. We may <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">re-evaluate</FONT> these features at a later date as additional guidance is provided by the Internal Revenue Service regarding the changes made to Section&nbsp;162(m) by the Tax Cuts and
Jobs Act. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><B><I>Information on Equity Compensation Plans as of March&nbsp;19, 2018 </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board recognizes that the increase in the number of shares under the Omnibus Plan will result in additional dilution or &#147;overhang&#148; for our stockholders,
although the incremental dilution would not be material. As commonly calculated, the total potential overhang resulting from the amendment of the Omnibus Plan would be approximately 3.88%, with the incremental overhang resulting from the share
increase equal to approximately 1.27%. This overhang is calculated as follows, in each case as of the record date of March&nbsp;19, 2018: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:10pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">year-to-date</FONT></FONT> grants during 2018. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table includes information regarding
